entry.title: cc: fix perfetto benchmark flow
entry.content:
The perfetto benchmark flow ends at the STEP_SEND_BEGIN_MAIN_FRAME,

when one tries to trace viz/benchmark categories, and starts

again at STEP_GENERATE_RENDER_PASS. It's only the case for multithreaded

cc instances as perfetto::TerminatingFlow is used.



To fix that and make the flow connected, change the TerminatingFlow

to a normal Flow.

entry.title: v4l2/stateless: Failure to queue buffer should not be fatal
entry.content:
The |output_queue_| and by extension, the ImageProcessor,

are not created until the first frame has received a surface.

In the creation of the surface a frame id is generated.

When an error occurs after the |output_queue_| is created

and before a compressed buffer is submitted the dtor

on the surface will try and enqueue the buffer associated

with the frame. This should not be a fatal error.

entry.title: documentScan: Clean up closed handles
entry.content:
Previously, DocumentScanAPIHandler kept all issued scanner and job

handles until a call to GetScannerList. This was needed because the

global list of available scanners could be updated outside activity from

a given extension. We didn't want an extension to unexpectedly get back

a kInvalid response if it hadn't done anything that should change the

scanner state. Since crrev.com/c/5241243, scanner tokens are tracked

separately for each extension, which means an extension's handles are

only invalidated through its own actions.



As a result, the api handler can clean up handles to avoid tracking them

forever once it knows they're invalid:

* When a scanner handle is closed, that handle is no longer valid. In

addition, any jobs pointing to the same handle are no longer valid.



* When a scanner is opened, any previous handles pointing to the same

scanner ID are no longer valid. Any job handles pointing to those

handles are also invalid.



There are other cases where DocumentScanAPIHandler could hypothetically

know that a handle is no longer valid (e.g. after seeing a response

containing a kDeviceMissing result). Such cases are not added here

because they would risk drifting out of sync with the specific behavior

of the backend. This risk does not apply to the two cases added here

because both of these are operations where the public API explicitly

documents that handles become invalid.



Because both of these are cases where the backend already invalidated

handles, this will cause no visible behavior change for extensions, but

allows DocumentScanAPIHandler to reduce the amount of state that has to

be tracked indefinitely.

entry.title: [IntersectionObserver] Fix margin treatment for cross-origin targets
entry.content:
The spec states that rootMargin and scrollMargin must be ignored for

any implicit-root observation that crosses origin boundaries.

Previously, there was no explicit mechanism in the code for enforcing

that; however, we still got the correct result as long as the

cross-origin iframe was process-isolated, because rootMargin is not

applied to LocalFrame::RemoteViewportIntersection() -- there is a

comment in the code to this effect.



However, if the cross-origin iframe was *not* process-isolated, then

the root margin would be incorrectly honored. Furthermore, the above

won't work correctly for scrollMargin.



This CL explicitly disables both rootMargin and scrollMargin for a

cross-site observation.

entry.title: Use base::ProtectedMemory to harden MojoJS enablement
entry.content:
This change uses base::ProtectedMemory, which was restored in

https://crrev.com/c/5161001 to harden MojoJS enablement against data-

only attacks.



The change adds a new static member to blink::ContextFeatureSettings

that is a base::ProtectedMemory. A method to set this value to

true is added, and is called in RenderFrameImpl in all code paths that

enable MojoJS for a RenderFrame.



Finally, the isMojoJSEnabled method of blink::ContextFeatureSettings,

is augmented to CHECK that the new base::ProtectedMemory

value is true if enable_mojo_js_ is true.



The result is that if a data-only attack is used to directly enable

MojoJS outside of the method calls, the CHECK will fail and crash the

process.



Tests to verify that all the normal code paths continue to properly

enable MojoJS, as well as tests that verify that tampering with the

vulnerable properties results in a crash have been added.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix WebStateObserverTest.UserInitiatedHashChangeNavigation
entry.content:
Before iOS 17.2, WebKit would return a nil WKNavigation for

browser-initiated same-document back/forward navigations. Logic

in CRWWebController relied on this behavior for deciding when

to mark a NavigationContext as same-document.



Starting in iOS 17.2, these navigations get a non-nil WKNavigation,

breaking the approach used by CRWWebController. This CL changes this

logic to directly check whether a navigation is same-document by

comparing the current and destination URLs. This fixes

WebStateObserverTest.UserInitiatedHashChangeNavigation on iOS 17.2+.
